<!-- Content -->

<p>
<b>Horreur sympathique</b><br>
</p>

<p>
De ce ciel bizarre et livide,<br>
Tourment&eacute; comme ton destin, <br>
Quels pensers dans ton &acirc;me vide<br>
Descendent? r&eacute;ponds, libertin.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Insatiablement avide<br>
De l'obscur et de l'incertain,<br>
Je ne geindrai pas comme Ovide<br>
Chass&eacute; du paradis latin.<br>
</p>

<p>
Cieux d&eacute;chir&eacute;s comme des gr&egrave;ves<br>
En vous se mire mon orgueil;<br>
Vos vastes nuages en deuil<br>
</p>

<p>
Sont les corbillards de mes r&ecirc;ves,<br>
Et vos lueurs sont le reflet<br>
De l'Enfer o&ugrave; mon coeur se pla&icirc;t.<br>
</p>
<p>&mdash; <i>Charles Baudelaire</i></p><br /><p>
<b>Reflected Horror</b><br>
</p>

<p>
From that sky, bizarre and livid, <br>
Distorted as your destiny, <br>
What thoughts into your empty soul <br>
Descend? Answer me, libertine.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Insatiably avid <br>
For the dark and the uncertain, <br>
I shall not whimper like Ovid <br>
Chased from his Latin paradise.<br>
</p>

<p>
Skies torn like the shores of the sea,<br>
You are the mirror of my pride;<br>
Your vast clouds in mourning<br>
</p>

<p>
Are the black hearses of my dreams, <br>
And your gleams are the reflection <br>
Of the Hell which delights my heart.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; William Aggeler, <i>The Flowers of Evil</i> (Fresno, CA: Academy Library Guild, 1954)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Sympathetic Horror</b>
</p>

<p>
From livid skies that, without end, <br>
As stormy as your future roll, <br>
What thoughts into your empty soul <br>
(Answer me, libertine!) descend?<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Insatiable yet for all <br>
That turns on darkness, doom, or dice, <br>
I'll not, like Ovid, mourn my fall, <br>
Chased from the Latin paradise.<br>
</p>

<p>
Skies, torn like seacoasts by the storm!<br>
In you I see my pride take form,<br>
And the huge clouds that rush in streams<br>
</p>

<p>
Are the black hearses of my dreams, <br>
And your red rays reflect the hell, <br>
In which my heart is pleased to dwell.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Roy Campbell, <i>Poems of Baudelaire</i> (New York: Pantheon Books, 1952)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Magnetic Horror</b>
</p>

<p>
"Beneath this sky, so livid and strange, <br>
Tormented like thy destiny, <br>
What thoughts within thy spirit range <br>
Themselves? &mdash; O libertine reply."<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; With vain desires, for ever torn <br>
Towards the uncertain, and the vast, <br>
And yet, like Ovid &mdash; I'll not mourn &mdash;<br>
Who from his Roman Heaven was cast. <br>
</p>

<p>
O heavens, turbulent as the streams, <br>
In you I mirror forth my pride! <br>
Your clouds, which clad in mourning, glide, <br>
</p>

<p>
Are the hearses of my dreams, <br>
And in your illusion lies the hell, <br>
Wherein my heart delights to dwell. <br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Cyril Scott, <i>Baudelaire: The Flowers of Evil</i> (London: Elkin Mathews, 1909)
</p>

<br>
<!-- Navigation -->

<div id="bottom">

<h3>Navigation</h3>

<p class="commentary">
Two editions of <i>Fleurs du mal</i> were published in Baudelaire's lifetime &mdash; one in 1857 and an expanded edition in 1861. "Scraps" and censored poems were collected in <i>Les &Eacute;paves</i> in 1866. After Baudelaire died the following year, a "definitive" edition appeared in 1868.
</p>

<ul>
	<li><a href="1857-table-of-contents">1857 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">First edition with 100 poems</div></li>
	<li><a href="1861-table-of-contents">1861 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">Second edition missing censored poems but including new ones</div></li>
	<li><a href="1866-les-epaves-table-of-contents">1866 Les &Eacute;paves</a><div class="nav-commentary">Twenty-three "scraps" including the poems censored from the first edition</div></li>
	<li><a href="1868-table-of-contents">1868 Fleurs du mal</a><div class="nav-commentary">Comprehensive edition published after Baudelaire's death</div></li>
	<li><a href="alphabetical-listing">All Poems (Alphabetical)</a><div class="nav-commentary">Every poem from each edition</div></li>
	<li><a href="audio/">Audio</a><div class="nav-commentary">Readings of Baudelaire mostly in French</div></li>
